<br>
Problem:<br>
Bards are forced to consistently 'twist' 3-4 songs at a time, consistently during their time online.  This causes wrist fatigue, injury, and can inhibit the player's enjoyment of the game thru lack of ability to socialize at times.<br>
<br>
Twisting was not intended for Bards when we were created, it just evolved into that.<br>
<br>
Solution:<br>
All Beneficial songs which appear in the 'Bard Buff Box' will be given a 6 minute duration (similar to Songblade).  You may only have a maximum of 3 songs running at one time.  Detrimental and songs that appear in the original 15 buff window will remain unchanged.  <br>
<br>
To use a detrimental song would force one beneficial song to drop per detrimental used.  This would prevent us gaining the ability to keep group songs up and dramatically increase our dps thru dots.<br>
<br>
IMHO this would be the easiest fix to a very old problem with Bards.  It would remove the need for a autotwist feature all together.  This would also require very minimal coding to implement.  All that would have to be done is change all beneficial songs to a 6 minute duration in the 'spell' data, and create a code to limit beneficial group songs to 3, which shouldn't be too hard.<br>
<br>
Thoughts? <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.ameritech.net/users/cjs27/twinkzignome.jpg"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://p201.ezboard.com/btheconcerthall.showUserPublicProfile?gid=falundirxviento>Falundir X Viento</A> at: 7/3/04 11:32 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#cccb9b><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://p201.ezboard.com/btheconcerthall.showUserPublicProfile?gid=talidd>Talidd</A></span><br> Posts: 116<br> <font color=#330000>(7/3/04 11:37 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://p201.ezboard.com/ftheconcerthallbackstage.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=19562.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> ..</span><hr size=1> No thanks.<br>
